chemistry for this work in 1998.</p>')" href="../programme/23"><img height="100"  src="../../images/series_system/kohn.jpg_100x100.jpeg" width="100" border="0" /></a></td><td class="table_top_spacer" valign="top" align="center" width="25%"><a title="<p>A science video interview with Wilson Greatbatch who originally graduated from Cornell and Buffalo universities is known for advancing the development of early implantable cardiac pacemakers. &nbsp; In this interview he discusses his work. &nbsp;</p>" onmouseover="return escape('<p>A science video interview with Wilson Greatbatch who originally graduated from Cornell and Buffalo universities is known for advancing the development of early implantable cardiac pacemakers. &nbsp; In this interview he discusses his work. &nbsp;</p>')" href="../programme/248"><img height="100"  src="../../images/series_system/greatbatch.jpg_100x100.jpeg" width="100" border="0" /></a></td></tr><tr><td class="table_bottom_spacer" valign="top" align="center" width="25%"><a title="<p>In this video scientist and Nobel Laureate Richard Ernst is interviewed by Nobel Laureate Harry Kroto and ex BBC Horizon producer Edward Goldwyn.&nbsp; Recorded 2003-2004.<br /><br />Nuclear magnetic resonance (nmr), a powerful technique for determining molecular structure, has totally revolutionised chemistry. From its inception half a century ago, its potential as an analytical tool for identifying compounds was clear, albeit limited by the fact that nmr is an intrinsically weak effect, requiring the most sensitive technology.</p>" onmouseover="return escape('<p>In this video scientist and Nobel Laureate Richard Ernst is interviewed by Nobel Laureate Harry Kroto and ex BBC Horizon producer Edward Goldwyn.&nbsp; Recorded 2003-2004.<br /><br />Nuclear magnetic resonance (nmr), a powerful technique for determining molecular structure, has totally revolutionised chemistry. From its inception half a century ago, its potential as an analytical tool for identifying com